# Tailwind-First Styling

When making UI or styling changes in this project, **always use Tailwind utility classes** directly in components.

## Do

- Put layout, spacing, colors, typography, hover/focus states, and responsive styles in `className` on the component
- Extend `tailwind.config.js` for reusable design tokens (colors, spacing, fonts) shared across the app
- Use Tailwind arbitrary values when needed: `bg-[#f3f3f3]`, `h-[calc(100svh-6rem)]`
- Hide scrollbars with utilities: `[scrollbar-width:none] [&::-webkit-scrollbar]:hidden`

## Don't

- Add new custom classes or blocks to `src/index.css` for component styling
- Create one-off `.my-component` CSS rules when Tailwind can express the same thing
- Duplicate values in both CSS variables and Tailwind unless required for third-party integration

## Exceptions (only when Tailwind is impractical)

- Third-party library overrides (e.g. Swiper styles)
- Existing global systems: `shopify-typography.css`, font imports, base resets
- Complex keyframe animations — prefer `tailwind.config.js` `keyframes` / `animation` over raw CSS

## Examples

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — new CSS in index.css
// .category-strip { height: 5.5rem; background: #f3f3f3; }

// ✅ GOOD — Tailwind on the component
<div className="h-[5.5rem] overflow-hidden shrink-0 bg-[#f3f3f3] border-t border-black/[0.04]">
```

When refactoring existing `index.css` styles, move them to Tailwind in the component (and update related files like hero overlap margins) rather than leaving split styling in both places.
